  "prompt": "What is Foot & Mouth Disease (FMD)?",
  "response": "Foot and Mouth Disease (FMD) is a highly contagious viral disease that affects livestock, particularly cloven-hoofed animals such as cattle, pigs, sheep, goats, and deer. It is caused by the Foot-and-Mouth Disease Virus (FMDV), which belongs to the Aphthovirus genus within the Picornaviridae family. \n\nFMD is characterized by fever and the development of vesicles (blisters) on the feet, mouth, snout, and teats. These vesicles can rupture, leading to painful sores that make eating and movement difficult for affected animals. \n\nThe disease spreads rapidly through direct contact with infected animals, contaminated farming equipment, vehicles, clothing, and via aerosols in the air. While FMD has a high morbidity rate, it usually has low mortality rates in adult animals but can be fatal in young animals.\n\nManaging and controlling FMD involves implementing strict biosecurity measures, vaccination programs, quarantine, and culling of affected and in-contact animals in some cases. FMD is a significant concern for the livestock industry due to its potential to cause severe economic losses and disrupt trade.",
